AGI - If we only analyze the data on voting intentions, today's Supermedia (as already happened on other recent occasions) brings good news for the majority of government. This applies in particular to Brothers of Italy, which makes a new positive rebound up to 30.2% – best given in the Supermedia since March 2023, almost two years ago.
<div </div
A growth that almost entirely drags that of the entire majority coalition (+0.5% in two weeks) since the other parties of the centre-right remain substantially stable. &nbsp; In the medium term, however, the most significant growth is that of the 5 Star Movement, which in the last 15 days has earned 0.5%. A positive trend that – unlike that of FDI – is the daughter of an increase recorded by all polling institutes present in the "paniere" of today's Supermedia. The party of Giuseppe Conte, in fact, in recent weeks has grown about half point in the estimates of SWG and Tecnè, of a point according to Noto and of 1.3% for Euromedia. But it is also a growth, in part, at the expense of the PD that in the same lasso of time goes down – even slightly – again falling below 23%.
<div </div
The fall of the party of Elly Schlein is confirmed almost univocally by 3 institutes on 4, having lost in the last half-point period according to SWG, Tecnè and Noto. In general, the whole of the parties forming the coalition of the center-left to the Policies of 2022 (besides the PD, the Green/Sinistra Alliance and More Europe) appears a bit in suffering, giving consensus on one side towards the M5S and on the other – even if in lower measure – to the former Third pole, namely Italy Viva and Action. &nbsp; As was said, therefore, for the centre-right, the present one seems to be a rather favourable conjunct, at least if one considers the intentions of national votes. But there are some signs that make it difficult to believe that the Meloni Government is experiencing a second honeymoon with voters, for example on a particularly “hot” theme like the economy: According to a recent Ipsos survey, it is a question that worries two Italians out of three (67%) and on which 54% believes that the management of the executive is negative.
<div </div
In addition, judgments towards the Meloni government detected by the Demos Institute, in its recent political atlas of February, are the lowest from the beginning of the legislature: only 40% of Italians give &nbsp; to the executive in office &nbsp; a vote equal to or greater than sufficiency. On the other hand, the idea that the majority is very stable &nbsp; it has never been so widespread:&nbsp; well 61% of respondents expect the Meloni&nbsp Government; it will be until the natural expiration of the legislature in 2027. &nbsp; But, in addition to the economy, there are at least two other themes that could be pushed for the majority.
&nbsp;
The first is that, dictated by the important developments in foreign policy, the creation of a single European army, and a possible involvement, in the near future, of the European military (including the Italian ones) to guarantee peace in Ukraine. A theme on which both Prime Minister Meloni and Minister Crosetto – and even more Minister Salvini – expressed themselves with words ranging from caution to conclaimed skepticism. Yet, according to SWG, the share of Italians in favour of the creation of a European army is increasing, and is equal to 57%. Not only: the favorable to the sending of Italian soldiers to Ukraine as deterrent to Russia are in number clearly greater than the contrary (49% against 37%) and are so much more among the voters of the majority parties (57%), than on this show a sensitivity not very dissimilar to that of voters of opposition parties (60%). &nbsp;
&nbsp;
Finally, another hot topic, culminated precisely today with the national strike of the magistrates, is that of justice. According to the recent surveys carried out by EMG, the Italians are not opposed to the North Reform which provides for the separation of careers, indeed: 52% believes it right, against 17% that believes it wrong. But support for mobilization – protest, and finally strike – of togae, is a theme that divides the country: 35% support them, while 37% condemn them; but only 19% of the citizens, two weeks ago, hoped that the planned strike for today would be revoked, in the face of a 33% indifferent. I note that many Italians are in solidarity with the judiciary although, in fact, they share the contents of the government's measures against which the magistrates protest so lively. And that too, in his own way, does not seem exactly a good signal for the executive. &nbsp;
&nbsp;
<em>NOTE: La&nbsp;Supermedia&nbsp;YouTrend/Agi is a weighted average of national polls on voting intentions. Today's weighting, which includes surveys carried out from 13 to 26 February, was carried out on 27 February on the basis of the sample consistency, the date of implementation and the method of data collection. The polls considered were made by Euromedia institutions (date of publication: 18 February), Noto (25 February), SWG (17 and 24 February) and Tecnè (15, 19 and 21 February). The detailed methodological note of each survey is available on the official site&nbsp;www.sondaggipoliticoelettorali.it.&nbsp;</em>
